{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2023}}
{{Discrimination sidebar|expanded=Policies}}
Many countries have laws, regulations, or recommendations that effectively prohibit donations of [[blood donation|blood]] or tissue for [[organ transplant|organ]] and [[corneal transplantation|corneal transplants]] from [[men who have sex with men]] (MSM), a classification irrespective of their [[Gay sexual practices|sexual activities with same-sex partners]] and of whether they [[Sexual identity|identify themselves]] as [[bisexual]] or [[gay]]. Temporary restrictions are sometimes called "deferrals", since blood donors who are found ineligible may be found eligible at a later date. However, many deferrals are indefinite meaning that donations are not accepted at any point in the future, constituting a [[de facto]] ban. Even men who have monogamous relations with their same-sex partners are found ineligible.

Since 1982, the risk for HIV infection transmitted via transfusion has been almost eliminated by the use of questionnaires to exclude donors at higher risk for HIV infection and performing screening tests with highly sensitive equipment to identify infected blood donations. According to the 2015 surveillance report by Canadian Blood Services, the risk of HIV transfusion-transmitted infection was fairly low: in 1 in 21.4 million donations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blood.ca/sites/default/files/External_Surveillance_Report_2015.pdf|title=Surveillance Report 2015|access-date=18 November 2019|archive-date=8 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210308135103/https://www.blood.ca/sites/default/files/External_Surveillance_Report_2015.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Contaminated haemophilia blood products|Contaminated blood]] put [[hemophilia|haemophiliacs]] at massive risk and severe mortality, increasing the risk of common surgical procedures. People who contracted HIV from a contaminated [[blood transfusion]] include [[Isaac Asimov]], who received a blood transfusion following cardiac surgery.

== HIV/AIDS ==
{{Main|Men who have sex with men#HIV/AIDS}}
In many high-income countries HIV is more prevalent among [[men who have sex with men]] (MSM) than among the general population.<ref name="unaids2006">{{cite web |year=2006 |title=At Risk and Neglected: four key populations |url=http://data.unaids.org/pub/GlobalReport/2006/2006_GR_CH05_en.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929191022/http://data.unaids.org/pub/GlobalReport/2006/2006_GR_CH05_en.pdf |archive-date=29 September 2011 |access-date=12 January 2022}}</ref>

In the United States the population most affected by HIV includes gay, bisexual, and other MSM.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/msm/index.html|title=HIV and Gay and Bisexual Men|date=12 November 2019|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> Of the 38,739 new HIV diagnoses in the US and dependent areas in 2017, 70% consisted of adult and adolescent gay and bisexual men.<ref name=":2" /> Although approximately 492,000 sexually active gay and bisexual men are at high risk for HIV, there are more tools to prevent HIV than ever before.<ref name=":2" />

Proponents of the lifetime restriction defend it because of the asserted risk of false negative test results<ref>{{cite news |last=Stier |first=Jeff |date=13 June 2007 |title=Blood for Sale |publisher=HuffingtonPost.com, Inc |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jeff-stier/blood-for-sale_b_52046.html |access-date=5 April 2008}}</ref> and because the MSM population in developed countries tends to have a higher prevalence of HIV/AIDS infection.<ref name="unaids2006" /> The UK government advisory committee, SABTO, stated in 2013 that "the risk of transfusion of HIV infected blood would increase if MSM were allowed to donate blood".<ref name="telegraph1aug2013">{{cite news |last1=Bloxham |first1=Andy |date=10 April 2011 |title=Homosexual men allowed to give blood but sex banned for decade |work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/8441054/Homosexual-men-allowed-to-give-blood-but-sex-banned-for-decade.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110411125844/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/8441054/Homosexual-men-allowed-to-give-blood-but-sex-banned-for-decade.html |archive-date=11 April 2011}}</ref> In July 2017 however, the UK government reduced the one year deferral window to three months, to take effect in the following months, resulting from SABTO's updated conclusions that "new testing systems were accurate and donors were good at complying with the rules". Furthermore, [[NHS Blood and Transplant]] are in the process of investigating how possible it is for MSM, depending on the degree of risk, to donate without even the three-month deferral.<ref name="bbcjul17">{{cite news |date=23 July 2017 |title=Blood donation rules relaxed for gay men and sex workers |publisher=BBC |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-40669950 |access-date=28 August 2017}}</ref> NHS has said that there is currently a limited amount of data on effective ways of conducting such risk assessments and that the initial steps of scoping, evidence gathering and testing will potentially take up to two years to complete.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Scientific review offers chance for more people to give blood |url=https://www.nhsbt.nhs.uk/news/scientific-review-offers-chance-for-more-people-to-give-blood/ |access-date=19 November 2019 |website=NHS Blood and Transplant |language=en}}</ref>

== Current situation ==
Restrictions vary from country to country, and in some countries, the practice of protected sex or periods of abstinence are not considered. The restrictions affect these men and, in some cases, any female sex partners. They do not otherwise affect other women, including [[women who have sex with women]]. With regard to blood donation, the [[United States Food & Drug Administration]] (FDA) enforces a three-month deferral period for MSM and women who have sex with MSM.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Commissioner |first=Office of the |date=2020-04-02 |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Update: FDA Provides Updated Guidance to Address the Urgent Need for Blood During the Pandemic |url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/coronavirus-covid-19-update-fda-provides-updated-guidance-address-urgent-need-blood-during-pandemic |access-date=2020-04-03 |website=FDA |language=en}}</ref> In Canada, the deferral period for MSM blood donors was decreased to 3 months in June 2019.<ref name="CAReport">{{Cite web |title=Canadian Blood Services Annual Report 2018–2019 |url=https://www.blood.ca/sites/default/files/CBS-AR2019-en.pdf |access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> Meanwhile, for tissues such as [[cornea]]s, the MSM deferral period is five years in the United States and 12 months in Canada.<ref name="Association of Federal Regulations in the United States and Canada With Potential Corneal Donation by Men Who Have Sex With Men">{{Cite journal |last1=Puente |first1=Michael A. |last2=Patnaik |first2=Jennifer L. |last3=Lynch |first3=Anne M. |last4=Snyder |first4=Blake M. |last5=Caplan |first5=Chad M. |last6=Pham |first6=Binhan |last7=Neves da Silva |first7=Helio V. |last8=Chen |first8=Conan |last9=Taravella |first9=Michael J. |last10=Palestine |first10=Alan G. |date=1 November 2020 |title=Association of Federal Regulations in the United States and Canada With Potential Corneal Donation by Men Who Have Sex With Men |url=https://doi.org/10.1001/jamaophthalmol.2020.3630 |journal=JAMA Ophthalmology |volume=138 |issue=11 |pages=1143–1149 |doi=10.1001/jamaophthalmol.2020.3630 |pmc=7516798 |pmid=32970105 |via=Silverchair}}</ref>

=== List of countries with their stand on MSM blood donors ===

This list shows countries that had restrictions on blood donors.<ref name="Seed">{{cite journal|journal=Transfusion|title=No evidence of a significantly increased risk of transfusion-transmitted human immunodeficiency virus infection in Australia subsequent to implementing a 12-month deferral for men who have had sex with men|first1=Clive R.|last1=Seed|first2=Philip|last2=Kiely|first3=Mathew|last3=Law|first4=Anthony J.|last4=Keller|volume=50|issue=12|pages=2722–2730|doi=10.1111/j.1537-2995.2010.02793.x|date=December 2010|pmid=20663106|s2cid=12106035|url=https://zenodo.org/record/897682}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodservices.ca/CentreApps/Internet/UW_V502_MainEngine.nsf/resources/Reports/$file/McLaughlin_Report.pdf|title=Mclaughlin Report on Risk Management for Canadian Blood Services|date=31 January 2007|publisher=McLaughlin Center for Population Health Risk Assessment, University of Ottawa|page=28|access-date=25 May 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080625001736/http://www.bloodservices.ca/CentreApps/Internet/UW_V502_MainEngine.nsf/resources/Reports/$file/McLaughlin_Report.pdf|archive-date=25 June 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Most national standards require direct questioning regarding a man's sexual history, but the length of deferral varies.

